      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Commercial FEA solver (Ansys Mechanical) used under vendor-maintained QMS; FDA in-house code subject to internal SQA plan. Both satisfy Gradation 2 documentation requirements.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical is a commercially validated solver with documented V&V and a vendor QMS. The FDA in-house FEA code operates under an internal SQA plan including version control, regression testing, and change control. Required level 2 is achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark problems from NAFEMS and Ansys verification manual executed; results agree with analytical solutions within 1% for linear static cases relevant to this COU.",
      "rationale": "Standard NAFEMS benchmark cases (e.g., linear elastic beam bending, contact patch test) were executed and results compared to analytical solutions. All benchmark errors were below 1%, satisfying the required verification level for this medium-risk COU."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study performed on screw shank and screw-rod interface regions; QoI change <2% between medium and fine mesh. Richardson extrapolation applied.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted. Construct stiffness changed by 1.4% and yield force by 1.7% between medium and fine meshes, both below the 2% convergence threshold. Richardson extrapolation confirmed discretization error contribution to total uncertainty is negligible relative to experimental variability."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative solver residuals monitored; force equilibrium residual <1e-6 at each load step. Consistent results across direct and iterative solvers.",
      "rationale": "Nonlinear static analysis used a Newton-Raphson scheme with force residual convergence criterion of 1e-6. Spot-check comparison between direct sparse solver and iterative PCG solver showed QoI differences below 0.1%, confirming numerical solver error is negligible."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent peer review of model setup, boundary conditions, and material assignments completed by analyst not involved in original model construction. Review checklist documented.",
      "rationale": "An independent analyst reviewed the model setup including boundary conditions, contact definitions, material property assignments, and load application against the ASTM F1717 test configuration. No discrepancies were identified. Review checklist archived in study documentation."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Continuum FEA with nonlinear geometry and elastic-perfectly-plastic titanium alloy material model. Frictional contact at screw-rod and rod-block interfaces. Model form justified by literature and sensitivity analysis.",
      "rationale": "The model employs nonlinear geometry (large displacement) and a bilinear isotropic hardening plasticity model for Ti-6Al-4V (E=114 GPa, yield 880 MPa, tangent modulus 1.1 GPa) consistent with published material data. Frictional contact (mu=0.2) at screw-rod and rod-UHMWPE block interfaces was validated against measured torque-preload relationships. Sensitivity analysis confirmed model form choices are the dominant uncertainty source, appropriately addressed by the validation comparison."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from coupon testing of production-lot Ti-6Al-4V; geometric inputs from CMM measurements of production screws. Input uncertainty quantified and propagated.",
      "rationale": "Elastic modulus, yield strength, and ultimate tensile strength were measured from five coupon specimens machined from the same production lot as the test constructs. Screw geometry was measured by CMM on three screws per lot. Input uncertainty (coefficient of variation <3% for material properties, <0.5% for geometry) was propagated via Monte Carlo to confirm its contribution to output uncertainty is small relative to model form uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N=11 constructs assembled from production-lot components at two independent laboratories. Sample size sufficient for statistical comparison per pre-defined analysis plan.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were assembled at two independent test laboratories (Lab A: n=6, Lab B: n=5) using components drawn from the same production lot. Pre-test CMM measurements confirmed screw geometry consistency. Sample size was determined by a pre-defined statistical power analysis targeting 80% power to detect a 10% QoI difference."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conducted under a single ASTM F1717 configuration (35 mm offset, room temperature, quasi-static). A second loading configuration or temperature condition would be required for Gradation 2.",
      "rationale": "Testing was performed under a single ASTM F1717 configuration (35 mm anterior offset, ambient temperature, displacement-controlled at 5 mm/min). Only one test condition was evaluated; the required level of 2 was not achieved. This is a documented limitation acknowledged in the credibility assessment; the overall package remains Accepted because the single condition is the clinically relevant worst-case scenario and all other factors meet or exceed required levels."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA model inputs (geometry, material, boundary conditions, loading) demonstrably equivalent to test conditions as verified by CMM measurements and test setup photographs.",
      "rationale": "FEA boundary conditions and geometry were set using CMM measurements of the actual test constructs. Test setup photographs and load cell calibration records were reviewed to confirm load application point, constraint locations, and fixture stiffness match the model. Screw insertion torque was measured and used to set bolt pretension in the FEA. Equivalency between model inputs and test conditions is well-established."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison using both percent difference (<10%) and normalized validation metric E/uval (<1.96) for all three QoIs. Comparison accounts for experimental variability.",
      "rationale": "Three QoIs (construct stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) were compared using the ASME V&V 40 normalized validation metric E/uval, where E is the model-experiment difference and uval is the combined experimental and model uncertainty. All three E/uval values were below 1.96 (stiffness: 0.87, yield force: 1.21, force at 40 mm: 1.54), and all percent differences were below the 10% pre-defined acceptance threshold."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) are directly linked to clinical failure modes (fatigue crack initiation, screw fracture) and regulatory submission requirements.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the three QoIs specified in ASTM F1717 and directly referenced in FDA guidance for pedicle screw system submissions. These QoIs are mechanistically linked to the dominant clinical failure mode (cyclic fatigue leading to screw fracture) through established fracture mechanics arguments. Relevance to the COU is high."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activity (ASTM F1717 bench test of production-lot constructs) is the same test specified in the COU; no extrapolation of validation evidence is required.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity is the ASTM F1717 static compression-bending test applied to the same non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw design and production-lot components that are the subject of the COU. There is no extrapolation of geometry, material, loading mode, or scale between the validation activity and the intended use. Relevance is maximal."
    }
  ],
